\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 SECRET}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 MINISTRY OF INFORMATION}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 HOME INTELLIGENCE WEEKLY REPORT
\par 
\par No. 167}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 16th December, 1943}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (Covering period from 7th to 14th December, 1943)
\par 
\par I. GENERAL COMMENTS
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 1. GENERAL}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par Spirits are at about the same level as last week. Pleasure is again reported at the successful outcome of the Teheran Conference; Mosley's release still causes some bitterness; but there is comparatively little comment on any war event, and personal af
fairs come first:
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid2910128 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
(a) The flu epidemic and illness generally are causing a good deal of depression, discomfort and inconvenience. Tiredness and war weariness arc also widely reported.
\par 
\par (b) Christmas. Though many look forward to Christmas as a rest and a break in the routine, there is much anxiety about Christmas fare and grumbling over the price and shortage of toys.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid16209235 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par Other home front topics: Scepticism over post-war prospects continues; so do complaints of insufficient coupons, particularly for renewing household goods; and problems of footwear, children's specially.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11.13.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 17)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 2. THE ALLIED CONFERENCES }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par Widespread satisfaction, particularly with the Teheran Conference, and strengthened hopes of an offens
ive in the West or the Balkans. Interest, however, does not appear to be intense, nor comment varied; .this is attributed to lack of information as to the decisions reached, and -to a certain impatience with "momentous conferences" - a desire for deeds no
t words.
\par 
\par First Cairo Conference: Much approval for the promises to China and the decisions about Japan. Many, however, feel that to announce the drastic curtailment of the' Japanese Empire is rather premature and over-confident. There is a slight incre
ase of interest in the Far Eastern War.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par Teheran Conference: Again great pleasure that "the Big Three" have met at last, that their meeting has been so cordial end that it appears to have resulted in complete agreement. The fact that Stalin has actual
ly been out of Russia is in itself considered "a wonderful stroke of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 business".
\par 
\par Accounts of the presentation of the Stalingrad Sword caused pleasure.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par Turkey and the second Cairo Conference: There is widespread speculation as to what Turkey will
 do. When the Churchill-Roosevelt Ineunu talks were first announced, there were high hopes that she would come into the war at once or in the near future. Now people seem loss hopeful and there is some irritation with optimistic press headlines which sugg
e
sted Turkey was about to enter the war. It is variously thought that she will do nothing till Rome has fallen or till we land on her shores to back her up, that the loss of the Dodecanese has discouraged hers that she will remain on the fence till the end
s and that she may even betray some of our secrets to the Germans.
\par 
\par The news presentation of the Conferences: Again criticism of our getting the news last. It is suggested that delays which allow the German radio to make announcements before our owns tend to make the public listen to and believe other items in enemy broad
casts. There is some criticism that the festive side of the Conferences was too much stressed; the reference to 37,500 eggs having been consumed being particularly resented. A few ask why Mr. Churchill is "always on the left of the pictures as if he ca
me third"..."and why his name is last in the signatures".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11.13.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 17 ten provincial P.Cs.)
\par 
\par 3. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 THE MOSLEY RELEASE }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par Discussion, though still widespread (Eleven Regions), is slowly dying down. It continues on the lines r
eported last week with feeling against the release strongest in industrial areas, and most support for Mr. Morrison's action among the middle-classes. Those who still feel strongly now allege that the voting after the debate clearly showed that Parliament
 is out of touch with public opinion (Four Regions). The growing minority who feel the Home Secretary is right are now inclined to blame the press for having exaggerated the whole affair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.9.10.11.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 17 one Special, twelve provincial P.Cs.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 4. ALLIED AIR OFFENSIVE }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par Great satisfaction-continues (Eight Regions), particularly with the raids on Berlin. Still more intense bombing is wanted. Losses in men and planes cause some anxiety.
\par 
\par The raid on Emden by the U.S.A.A.F. (Decembe
r 11) is praised (Three Regions), though there is some scepticism about the claim of German fighters destroyed (Two Regions); from a third Region it is reported that U.S. claims are thought to drop when our fighters accompany their bombers.
\par 
\par People variously feel the air offensive is shortening the war (Three Regions), making the second front unnecessary and saving many soldiers' lives (Two Regions each).
\par 
\par However, regret among a minority at the killing of German civilians and the general destructio
n is reported from six Regions. It is said there can be no rejoicing at the smashing of homes. On the other hand a "storm of anger" is said to have been aroused in the diocese by the Bishop of Gloucester's Diocesan Letter in which he roundly condemned the
 bombing of Germany. It is felt he should retire if he can't stop "upsetting folk"; and that such sentiments should not be publicised in wartime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 17 eleven provincial P.Cs.)
\par 
\par 5. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 REPRISALS AND SECRET WEAPONS }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par A few people in London, the South East and the North feel apprehensive about reprisals; people in other parts are "undisturbed".
\par 
\par Discussion of the secret weapon threat has declined (Three Regions) and little concern is now reported.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (1.2.3.5.5SE.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 17 two provincial P.Cs.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 6. RUSSIA}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par Admiration for the Russian progress continues widespread. People are pleased that recent German counter-offensives achieved so little, but a minority fear that Kiev may be recaptured by the Germans. There is some speculation about a Russian winter offen
sive.
\par 
\par Speculation is also reported about the extent of Russian influence after the war (Five Regions). Whilst most are hoping for post-war co-operation with Russia, there are still a number who view post-war Russia with doubt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9. 10.13.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 17 two provincial P.Cs.) 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 7. ITALY}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par There are still many references to disappointingly slow progress, which leaves the enemy far too much time to dig himself in. Nevertheless some arc satisfied that the advance, if slow, is sure. People are said to realise the toughness of the going.
\par 
\par There is again praise for the 5th and 8th Armies which are fighting under such difficult conditions. Some people are beginning to feel that this front is only a side-show..."we are not falling into the trap 
of concentrating large forces there and playing into German hands".
\par 
\par Despite the announcement about an Italian unit fighting alongside our men, the Italians are still looked on as not being of much use. It is thought that a much firmer attitude should be adopted to protect our troops from Italian profiteering,}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 8. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 WAR AT SEA}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par General satisfaction with the recently announced defeat of the two U-boat attacks on an Atlantic convoy. In three Regions the news is said to have been accepted as further
 proof that the battle of the Ltlantic has been won. The results are thought to speak well for the co-ordination of the Services engaged.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (1.2.3.5.5SE.6.7.8.10.13)
\par 
\par 9. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 LORD WOOLTON'S SPEECH IN THE HOUSE OF LORDS (DECEMBER 8) AND POST-WAR PLANNING}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par There has not been much comment, but the speech appears to have been well received. Opinion is, however, divided between those who think it was wise not to promise too much, and those who feel that promises are necessary in reconstruction: "We want to 
know what we've got ahead of us".
\par 
\par Post-war planning: Fears continue to outweigh hopes. Some regard Lord Woolton's appointment and speech as clear signs that the Government is really beginning to plan. But many - particularly workers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 - remain skeptical.
\par 
\par Homes, jobs and social security continue the main pre-occupations.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.10.11.13.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 17 one Special, six provincial P.Cs.)
\par 
\par 10.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 GENERAL SMUTS' ADDRESS (NOVEMBER 25)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par Praise continues for what is generally regarded as a personal expression of opinion by a realistic and far-sighted statesman.
\par 
\par Most comment is about his references to France; opinion is divided between those who approve his outspokenness and those who regard it as ill-timed and likely to damage Anglo-French relations.
\par 
\par A few people think he was "put up" by the Government to make the remarks. His references to Britain being poor after the war also arouse mixed feelings. Some say it is time we faced this fact; others that it is nonsense.
\par 
\par Reports from four Regions refer to some speculation about the delay in publishing the speech. 
\par 
\par (1.2.3.4.6.7.8.9.10.13.17 Seven provincial P.Cs.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 11. YUGOSLAVIA}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par There is confusion about the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 guerrilla}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  forces, and about the merits of the rival generals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (1.2.3.5.5SE.6.11)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 12. THE FRENCH}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par Criticism of the French, in part stimulated by the Lebanese affair continues on a reduced scale.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (1.3.5.5SE.8)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 13. BROADCASTING AND PRESENTATION OF NEWS}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par Little comment on news presentation. Complaints continue of the inaccuracy of news (Four Regions), the press being especially criticised for over emphasizing minor}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16209235 points and for sensational headlines. There is also criticism of delay in releasing news, thus allowing German stations to announce it before us (Four Regions).}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par Programmes: B.B.C. entertainment programmes are again criticised: too much modern music and jazz, and too little good music (Four Regions). Broadcast plays are liked and more would be appreciated (Three Regions).
\par 
\par The Mayor of Narvik\rquote s postscript, December 5, is highly praised (Five Regions)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128  [illegible]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  one of the most memorable postscripts given".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 II. SPECIAL COMMENTS 
\par SHORT WEEKLY REVIEW}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 14. HEALTH}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par The prevalence of influenza is widely reported this week (Eleven Regions), although in two Regions the epidemic is thought to be past its peak. People are said to be very tired arid to lack resistance.
\par 
\par The prevalence of illness generally is variou
sly attributed to food deficiencies, long hours of work and extra duties, the black-out, poor quality shoes and lack of warm under-clothing, long waits for transport in bad weather, and overcrowded buses. Official statements concerning the good health of 
the-nation are looked on as contrary to experience and cause irritation..."it is clear that resistance to infection is generally much lower".
\par 
\par Doctors: The shortage of civilian doctors and the proposed further call-up for the army, when the civilian med
ical profession is so over-worked, is causing some concern. The temporary releases of some army doctors for civilian work is welcomed. Long and weary waits in surgeries which sometimes remain open until 10.30 p.m. are reported, and it is thought that many
 people "just drag. on as best they can".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 17 one Special, six provincial P.Cs.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 15. THE BALLOT FOR THE MINES }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par There has again been considerable comment on the scheme. The general reaction has been a mixture of approval and criticism; it is felt to be a "necessary evil\'94.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 Approval: The scheme is generally accepted as fair and democratic (Eight Regions). Some, particularly miners, have doubts, however, as to whether it will be equally fair in practice (Three Regions).
 Exemption, it is feared, will be too easily obtained by those with education and influence.
\par 
\par Criticisms: Chief criticisms of the scheme have been as follows
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid2910128 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (a) It is impractical (Six Regions), because:
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li851\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin851\itap0\pararsid2910128 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (i) Such "haphazard" selection will mean many misfits (Five Regions).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2910128 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (ii) "Green labour" will not provide the required production (Four Regions). Miners think the war will be over before the boys become adequately proficient.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid2910128 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par (b) It is unfair to force boys into the mines, while strikes are tolerated (Two Regions).
\par 
\par (c) It has been made necessary by "muddling" in the past (Two Regions).
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid16209235 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par The boys themselves are said not to relish the idea of mining instead of the Forces. Some are saying that they will refuse to enter the industry}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9123155  [illegible] }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
"prison before the pits". Mothers are in many cases equally anxious.
\par 
\par Alternatives suggested are: The release of miners from the Force and industry (Eight Regions), nationalisation of the mines (Six Regions) and "settling the miners\rquote  grievances" (Three Regions).
\par 
\par Other points raised have been:
\par 
\par Cadets: The waste of training is deplored (Five Regions). It is felt that membership of the various corps will suffer accordingly.
\par 
\par Billeting: It is feared that mining families and billetees will not mix very successfully (Four Regions).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9123155 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 17 five provincial P.Cs.)
\par 
\par 16. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9123155 TOYS AND OTHER CHRISTMAS PRESENTS}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par There are many complaints of the shortage, high price and poor quality of toys (Seven Regions), and the difficulty of providing Presents for children. There is also comment on the 
difficulty of finding "seasonal goods" and on the exorbitant price of fancy articles.
\par 
\par The following are each mentioned in one Regional report:
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9123155 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid9123155 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (a) Appreciation for the release of more toys.
\par 
\par (b) The announcement that retailers may now sell sec
ond-hand metal toys acquired from private individuals has been received with the comment; "It'll just be a racket". Some think that the sale of home-made and second-hand toys generally is "a regular ramp which should be looked into without delay".
\par 
\par (c) Christmas cards, on sale at high prices in spite of paper shortage and restrictions, are the object of criticism.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid16209235 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9123155 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (1.2.3.5.5SE.6.7.10)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9123155 17. FOOD}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid16209235\charrsid9123155 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 General satisfaction remains, although comment continues about the shortage of fish (Five Regions), and the smallness of the present milk ration (Four Regions).
\par 
\par Other topics now in the public mind are:
\par 
\par Christmas fare (Eleven Regions):
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid9123155 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
(a) Turkeys (Eight Regions). Hopes and fears - mostly the latter - regarding the prospects of getting a turkey are widespread. A few complain that hotels and large towns are to have all the turkeys and other poultry.
\par 
\par (b) "Extras" (Five Regions). There is some disappointment and crumbling at the "limited" Christmas food this year.
\par 
\par (c) Profiteering and black market (Four Regions), especially in -turkeys and whisky are criticised. One Region mentions America "encouragement" in this respect; Americans are said to be offering up to 26 for a small turkey.
\par 
\par (d) Shortage of dried fruit (Three Regions) is anticipated with disappointment.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par (e) Christmas and Now Year drinks: People in Scotland and the South East are anxious about supplies. 
\par 
\par (f)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 An increased sweets ration over Christmas is hoped for by a few (Two Regions).
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid16209235 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
Food for invalids and old people (Five Regions): These people's "plight" is regretted. It is felt that the shortage of milk, fish and oranges enhance'}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 problem.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9123155 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11.13. 17 one Special, twelve provincial P.Cs.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9123155 18. HOUSING AND BILLETING}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par Complaints and anxiety continue to be reported on familiar lines.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9123155 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (2.3.4.5.6.7.9.10.)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9123155 19. CLOTHING}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par 
\par Comment on the usual lines, with special reference to:
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9123155 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid9123155 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
(a) Footwear difficulties (Eleven Regions), particularly shortage and poor- especially for children; also the difficulty of getting shoes repaired and the delay entailed.
\par 
\par (b) The shortage of coupons generally, particularly for replacing household goods (Nine Regions), and for children.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid16209235 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
\par Extra coupons for larger children: A few complaints of or inequality are reported (Three Regions) Some inefficiency on the part of the schools is alleged. One report refers to a school whore children were refused coupons if they were absent on the day 
of examination. Another mentions a child who just missed the extra coupons by \'bd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 
on the day he was measured, yet whose feet were of the requisite size by October 31, the final date for measuring. In these tests, much is said to depend on the teacher. It is asked when there will be further tests.
\par 
\par Some complain of the conditions, not understanding by "growing boys just under the height limit, but with small feet, get no coupons, yet a small child with large foot gets extra".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9123155 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16209235 17 one special, five provincial P.Cs.)
